{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# op-cert: trusted gate service — authoritative-state fetch, per-kind dispatch, async job API (+ client command)\n\n## Why\nFor high assurance, a developer routes a gate run to a trusted environment that fetches\nauthoritative state ITSELF (ticket state from the tickets branch; code at the review remote's\n`main` tip), runs the gate, and returns an Ed25519-signed `rebar.opcert.v1` cert — so\nclient-supplied inputs cannot forge a pass (the SLSA non-falsifiable-provenance principle). This\nstory builds the **service and its client half only**; AWS IaC + the real deploy are the sibling\n\"AWS IaC + deploy\" story, and the signing behavior itself ships in the \"producer signing seam\"\nstory this depends on. All design forks are settled in the epic's \"Producer-signing &\ncompute-runtime design resolution\" section — this story implements, it does not decide.\n\n**Hard dependencies (not yet on `main`):** the op-cert substrate consumed here\n(`signing.sign_opcert_manifest`, `src/rebar/attest/opcert.py`, `trusted_env.py`, `sshsig.sign` —\nGerrit changes 649/650/660, in review), the merge-gate consumer `rebar verify-opcert` (story 4214,\nGerrit change 664, in review — referenced by the client ACs below), and the producer signing seam\nstory must land first;\nmentions of them below are forward references to that stack, enforced by this ticket's\n`depends_on` links. `src/rebar/review_bot/app.py` (the pattern mirrored) IS on `main` today.\n\n## What\n**Service** (`src/rebar/opcert_service/`, library-mode: rebar imported behind a thin FastAPI app —\nthe `review_bot/app.py` software pattern; NOT the stdio `rebar-mcp`):\n- **Async job API** (gate runs take 30s–minutes; no sync request can hold): `POST /opcert/jobs`\n  validates, enqueues on an in-process `asyncio.Queue`, returns **202 `{job_id}`**;\n  `GET /opcert/jobs/{job_id}` returns the job record. Single background worker drains serially\n  under a bounded per-run timeout: default **900 s** (gate runs take 30s–minutes; the ceiling is\n  generous), configurable via `REBAR_OPCERT_JOB_TIMEOUT_SECONDS`. Job state is in-memory (a restart loses queued jobs; clients\n  re-submit — cert minting is idempotent).\n- **Request schema**: `{\"ticket_id\": str, \"kind\": \"completion-verifier\"|\"plan-review\"}` — ONLY\n  identifiers. Any other client field (a `material_fingerprint`, a `commit`, an `env_id`) is\n  IGNORED; the server derives every authoritative value itself.\n- **Authoritative fetch**: the worker fetches the tickets branch (ticket state) and the review\n  remote's `main` tip (code) with its own read-only credentials, sets\n  `merged_log_commit = <fetched main HEAD sha>`, and computes the material fingerprint itself.\n- **Per-kind dispatch + native verdicts (no unified enum)**: `plan-review` →\n  `rebar.llm.review_plan(...)` (verdict `PASS|BLOCK|INDETERMINATE`); `completion-verifier` →\n  `rebar.llm.verify_completion(...)` (verdict `PASS|FAIL`). A raised\n  `LLMError`/`LLMUnavailableError` maps to the job's transport status — never a fabricated\n  verdict. Response/job schema:\n  `{status: \"queued\"|\"running\"|\"completed\"|\"error\", kind, verdict: <native enum>|null,\n  envelope: <encoded DSSE>|null, material_fingerprint, merged_log_commit, error: {class, message}|null}`\n  — `envelope` present ONLY on a `PASS` verdict.\n- **Signing = the producer seam, once; the service only PROVISIONS the key.** The gate\n  producers mint the op-cert via the signing seam (producer-seam story); the handler itself\n  never calls a sign function and never passes `sign=False`. The hand-off protocol: this story\n  adds one override to the seam's key resolution — `REBAR_OPCERT_KEY_PATH` (an explicit key\n  file path) takes precedence over the `<tracker>/.opcert-key` genesis. Before dispatching a\n  job, the worker fetches the SSM SecureString (`/rebar/prod/opcert-ed25519-key`),\n  **materializes it to a 0600 `mkstemp` temp file** (SSHSIG signing shells\n  `ssh-keygen -Y sign -f <path>` and needs a file path), sets `REBAR_OPCERT_KEY_PATH` to that\n  path and `REBAR_OPCERT_ENV_ID` as the principal for the gate run, and **deletes the file in a\n  `finally`** — never persisted, and the seam signs exactly once with the provisioned key. The\n  key MUST be passphrase-free (`ssh-keygen -Y sign` is non-interactive). The legacy HMAC\n  environment key is never provisioned in the server.\n- **Stateless / store-read-only**: the server writes NOTHING to the tickets branch; it returns the\n  envelope and the client persists it. Endpoint authn (SigV4) is terminated at API Gateway (the\n  IaC story); the app additionally requires a shared secret as defense in depth — same posture as\n  `review_bot`'s check (which uses a `?token=` query parameter, `review_bot/app.py`); the opcert\n  app checks an `X-Opcert-Guard` **header** instead, because API Gateway injects static request\n  headers on the integration.\n- **Container image**: `infra/compose/Dockerfile.opcert` (build context = repo root, per the\n  review_bot Dockerfile pattern) installing **OpenSSH ≥ 8.9** and running\n  `uvicorn rebar.opcert_service.app:app`.\n\n**Client** (`src/rebar/_commands/remote_cert.py`, CLI `rebar remote-cert <ticket-id> <kind>`):\n- Reads `verify.opcert_remote_url` (new `VerifyConfig` key, `str | None = None`; unset → clear\n  error; nothing remote is ever required for local operation). SigV4-signs the request with\n  ambient AWS credentials, submits the job, polls to a terminal status, and on `PASS` **persists\n  the returned envelope + bound fields as the `SIGNATURE` event** (the same event shape\n  `sign_opcert_manifest` appends; auto-pushed with the tickets branch). Safe because the envelope\n  is self-authenticating — tampering with the bound values breaks the signature the merge gate\n  (`rebar verify-opcert`) verifies. Non-PASS / error → non-zero exit with the job's error class.\n\n## Scope\n- In: the FastAPI service, dispatch/verdict mapping, authoritative fetch, SSM-parameter key\n  materialization + the `REBAR_OPCERT_KEY_PATH` seam override, Dockerfile, the `remote-cert` client command, `verify.opcert_remote_url`.\n- Out: Terraform/API Gateway/SSM resources + the real deploy + live round-trip\n  (the \"AWS IaC + deploy\" story); the producer signing seam itself (dependency); HMAC removal\n  (8f1d).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `POST /opcert/jobs` ACKs 202 `{job_id}` and `GET /opcert/jobs/{id}` reaches a terminal\n      status via the background worker; a test drives the round-trip against a fake authoritative\n      source with the request/response schemas above.\n- [ ] Integrity test (the load-bearing one): a request carrying a **doctored\n      `material_fingerprint`** and a doctored `commit` is accepted, the extra fields are ignored,\n      and the signed op-cert's bound `material_fingerprint`/`merged_log_commit` equal the values\n      the server derived from its own fetch — a client cannot influence any bound value.\n- [ ] Per-kind verdict mapping: tests assert `plan-review` jobs surface\n      `PASS|BLOCK|INDETERMINATE` natively, `completion-verifier` jobs surface `PASS|FAIL`, a\n      raised `LLMError` yields `status=\"error\"` with `verdict=null`, and `envelope` is non-null\n      ONLY on `PASS` (BLOCK/FAIL/INDETERMINATE/error all return `envelope: null`).\n- [ ] Key materialization: a test asserts the SSM SecureString value is written to a 0600\n      `mkstemp` file for the `ssh-keygen -Y sign` invocation and that NO key file remains after\n      signing (including on a raised exception — the `finally` path).\n- [ ] The server appends no tickets-branch event: a test asserts the store is unchanged after a\n      completed job; `rebar remote-cert` persists the returned envelope as a `SIGNATURE` event\n      that `verify_signature`/`rebar verify-opcert` then certify, and a tampered envelope is\n      rejected (`mismatch`).\n- [ ] Offline default preserved: a test asserts every local op-cert sign/verify path works with\n      `verify.opcert_remote_url` unset and no network — the remote path is opt-in and its absence\n      never blocks a local operation.\n- [ ] `infra/compose/Dockerfile.opcert` installs OpenSSH ≥ 8.9 and starts the service; a test\n      asserts the Dockerfile declares both.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` green."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784005140569977001,"uuid":"34840a68-1f0d-451c-95ad-1a17a201cfe8"}